text:
Swisscom AG is the leading telecommunications and information technology company in Switzerland. It is headquartered in Ittigen, near Bern, and offers an extensive range of services including mobile and fixed-line telephony, broadband internet, digital television, and various IT solutions. In addition to its robust presence in Switzerland, Swisscom has a significant presence in Italy through its subsidiary, Fastweb, which provides comprehensive telecommunications services.

Swisscom's origin dates back to 1851 with the establishment of a state-run telegraph service in Switzerland. The service evolved over the years, eventually becoming part of the PTT (Post, Telegraph, and Telephone) in 1920. In 1997, the telecommunications division was separated from postal services, leading to the creation of Swisscom. It was partially privatized in 1998 through a public offering on the Swiss stock exchange. Notably, Swisscom acquired a majority stake in the Italian telecom company Fastweb in 2007 for approximately 5 billion CHF, enhancing its position in the European market.

The company is organized into several segments: Swisscom Switzerland, which serves residential and business customers within the country; Fastweb, which operates in Italy; and various other subsidiaries and brands. Swisscom holds a dominant position in the Swiss market, with significant market shares in mobile communications (56%), broadband internet (51%), and digital television (37%).

Financially, Swisscom reported revenues exceeding 11 billion CHF in 2023, demonstrating consistent performance. The company is committed to innovation and sustainability, investing heavily in research and development and initiatives that reduce environmental impact.

In March 2024, Swisscom announced a strategic plan to merge its subsidiary Fastweb with Vodafone Italia, aiming to strengthen its position in the Italian market.

Swisscom is partly owned by the Swiss government, which holds a 51% stake. It employs approximately 19,729 full-time equivalents and is committed to workforce development, offering numerous apprenticeships and training programs. Despite facing competition within Switzerland, Swisscom maintains a leading market position. The company has also been at the forefront of technological advancements, launching its 5G network in 2019.
